name: Ruby
definition: High-level object oriented programming language. Supports multiple paradigms, e.g. functional, imperative

name: Android
definition: Mobile operating system based on the Linux kernel

name: Structured Query Language
definition: Special programming language for managing data in a relational database management system (RDBMS), or for stream processing in a relational data stream management system (RDSMS).

name: SQL
definition: see Structured Query Language

name: C#
definition: High level programming language within the .NET framework.

name: Procedural Language
definition: Property of a programming language where the language executes as a sequence of statements that lead to a result. Typically uses variables and loops.

name: Ruby on Rails
definition: Server-side web application framework written in Ruby

name: Git
definition: Version control system for tracking changes in files. Primarily used for source code management.

name: GitHub
definition: Web-based repositroy hosting service for Git version control.

name: Unity
definition: Cross-platform game engine

name: Functional Language
definition: Programming paradigm where computation is treated as evaluation of mathematical functions, avoids changing state and mutable data, and programming is done declaratively. Expressions or declarations are used instead of statements.

name: Java
definition: High-level, object oriented programming language.

name: Python
definition: High-level, interpreted programming language.
maker: Guido van Rossum; Python Software Foundation

name: Microsoft SQL Server
definition: A prprietary relational database management sytem.

name: RDBMS
definition: see Relational Database Management System

name: Relational Database Management System
definition: Database management system based on a relational model.

name: OOP
definition: see Object Oriented Programming

name: Object Oriented Programming
definition: Programming paradigm based on 'objects' which contain data and methods.

name: iOS
definition: Mobile operating system for Apple mobile devices.

name: Front-end
definition: Web development where HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are used to produce a website or web application

name: Back-end
definition: Data-access and server logic layers in web development.

name: HTML
definition: see Hypertext Markup Language

name: Hypertext Markup Language
definition: Markup language for creating web pages and web applications.
maker: World Wide Web Consortium; Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group

name: Markup Language
definition: System for annotating a document that is syntactially distinguishable from text, and often prescribes presentation rules for structured data.

name: CSS
definition: see Cascading Style Sheets

name: Cascading Style Sheets
definition: Style sheet language used to describe the presentation of a document written in a markup language.
maker: Hakon Wium Lie; Bert Bos; World Wide Web Consortium

name: JavaScript
definition: High-level, interpreted programming language used in web development.
maker: Brendan Eich; Netscape; Mozilla; Ecma International

name: jQuery
definition: Open-source Javascipt library designed to simplify client-side scripting of HTML.

name: AJAX
definition: see Asynchronous JavaScript and XML

name: Asynchronous JavaScript and XML
definition: Set of client-side web technology that allow data to be sent and received from a server asynchronously, without disrupting the behavior of an existing page.

name: REST
definition: see Representational State Transfer

name: Representational State Transfer
definition: Architecture style for web services that calls for the manipulation of text-based web resources using stateless operations.

name: MVC
definition: see Model-View-Controller

name: Model-View-Controller
definition: Software concept where an application is divided into three interconnected parts to separate data from visual presentation. Model refers to underlying information, controller deals with the logic of manipulating information, and the view displays the application to the user based on the underlying data.

name: Flask
definition: A python web application framework that is classified as a microframework because of its minimalism.

name: XML
definition: see Extensible Markup Language

name: Extensible Markup Language
definition: Markup language that defines rules for encoding documents using a textual data format.
maker: Tim Bray; Jean Paoli; C. M. Sperberg-McQueen; Eve Maier; Francois Yergeau; John Cowan

name: ECMAScript
definition: Scripting language specification created to standardize JavaScript. JavaScript is its most common implementation, but also includes others like ActionScript.

name: ActionScript
definition: Object-oriented programming language within the ECMAScript specification mainly used for developing websites and software targeting Adobe Flash Player.

name: Clojure
definition: Dialect of the Lisp programming language with a focus on functional programming.

name: Django
definition: Open-source web application framework using Python.
maker: Adrian Holovaty; Simon Willison; Django Software Foundation

name: Haskell
definition: Purely functional programming language.
maker: Lennart Augustsson; Dave Barton; Brian Boutel; Warren Burton; Joseph Fasel; Kevin Hammond; Ralf Hinze; Paul Hudak; John Hughes; Thomas Johnsson; Mark Jones; Simon Peyton Jones; John Launchbury; Erik Meijer; John Peterson; Alastair Reid; Colin Runciman; Philip Wadler

name: Lisp
definition: Family of programming languages. Second-oldest high-level language after Fortran.
maker: John McCarthy; Steve Russell; Timothy P. Hart; Mike Levin
